{{for|the Biblical Mount Sinai, and a discussion of its possible locations|Biblical Mount Sinai}} {{Other places}} {{Redirect|Jabal Musa|other uses|Jebel Musa (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Sinai ({{transl|ar|ALA|Ṭūr Sīnāʼ}}) | photo =Mount Moses.jpg | photo_caption = The summit of Mount Sinai | photo_size = 250 | elevation_m = 2,285 | elevation_ref = | location = [[South Sinai Governorate|Sinai]], [[Egypt]] | map = Egypt Sinai | map_caption = Sinai Peninsula, showing location of Mount Sinai | map_size = 150 | coordinates = {{coord|28|32|23|N|33|58|24|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | range = }} '''Mount Sinai''' ({{lang-ar|طُور سِينَاء|Ṭūr Sīnāʼ}} or {{lang-arz|جَبَل مُوسَىٰ|Jabal Mūsā|lit=Mountain of Moses}}; {{lang-syc|ܛܘܪܐ ܕܣܝܢܝ}} or {{lang-syc|ܛܘܪܐ ܕܡܘܫܐ}}; {{lang-he-n|הַר סִינַי}}, ''Har Sinai''; {{lang-el|Όρος Σινάι}}; {{lang-la|Mons Sinai}}), also known as '''Mount Horeb''' or '''Gabal Musa''', is a mountain in the [[Sinai Peninsula]] of [[Egypt]] that is a possible location of the [[biblical Mount Sinai]], which is considered a holy site by the [[Abrahamic religion]]s. Mount Sinai is mentioned many times in the [[Book of Exodus]] and other books of the [[Bible]],<ref>Joseph J. Hobbs, ''Mount Sinai'' (University of Texas Press) 1995, discusses Mount Sinai as geography, history, ethnology and religion.</ref> and the [[Quran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qtafsir.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1145&Itemid=151 |title=Tafsir Ibn Kathir |publisher=qtafsir.com |date=2002-10-26 |accessdate=2015-01-30}}</ref> According to [[Judaism|Jewish]], [[Christianity|Christian]], and [[Islam]]ic tradition, the biblical Mount Sinai was the place where [[Moses]] received the [[Ten Commandments]].
==Geography== Mount Sinai is a {{convert|2285|m|ft|adj=on}} moderately high mountain near the city of [[Saint Catherine, Egypt|Saint Catherine]] in the Sinai region. It is next to [[Mount Catherine]] (at {{convert|2629|m|ft|abbr=on|disp=or}}, the highest peak in [[Egypt]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allsinai.info/sites/geology.htm|publisher=AllSinai.info|title=Sinai Geology}}</ref> It is surrounded on all sides by higher peaks of the mountain range.
==Geology== Mount Sinai's rocks were formed in the late stage of the [[Arabian-Nubian Shield]]'s (ANS) evolution. Mount Sinai displays a [[Ring dike|ring complex]]<ref>[http://www.virtualacademia.com/pdf/rad586_598.pdf Hanaa M. Salem and A. A. ElFouly, "Minerals Reconnaissance at Saint Catherine Area, Southern Central Sinai, Egypt and their Environmental Impacts on Human Health"]. ICEHM2000, Cairo University, Egypt, September 2000, pp. 586–98</ref> that consists of alkaline [[Granite|granites]] intruded into diverse rock types, including [[Volcanic rock|volcanics]]. The granites range in composition from [[syenogranite]] to alkali feldspar granite. The volcanic rocks are alkaline to peralkaline and they are represented by subaerial flows and eruptions and [[subvolcanic rock|subvolcanic]] [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]]. Generally, the nature of the exposed rocks in Mount Sinai indicates that they originated from differing depths.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}
==Religious significance== [[File:Mt. Sinai (Georgian MSS).jpg|left|thumb|Mount Sinai depicted on late medieval Georgian manuscript.]] [[File:A Greek Orthodox Chapel at the top of Mount Sinai.jpg|thumb|A Greek Orthodox Chapel at the top of Mount Sinai at night]] [[File:Greek Orthodox Chapel at top of Mt Sinai.jpg|thumb|A Greek Orthodox Chapel at the top of Mount Sinai]] [[File:MasjidMountSinai.jpg|thumb|A [[mosque]] at the top of Mount Sinai]] {{main|Biblical Mount Sinai|Saint Catherine's Monastery}} The biblical Mount Sinai is one of the most important sacred places in the [[Judaism|Jewish]], [[Christianity|Christian]] and [[Islam]]ic religions.
According to the [[Hebrew Bible]],<ref>''Exodus'' 19 </ref> it was the mountain where [[God]] gave laws to the [[Israelites]]. However, the earliest Christian traditions place this event at the nearby [[Mount Serbal]], at the foot of which a monastery was founded in the 4th century; it was only in the 6th century that the monastery moved to the foot of [[Mount Catherine]], following the guidance of [[Josephus]]' earlier claim that Sinai was the highest mountain in the area.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
The earliest references to Jebel Musa as Mount Sinai or Mount Sinai being located in the present-day Sinai peninsula are inconclusive. There is evidence that prior to 100 CE, well before the Christian monastic period, Jewish sages equated Jebel Musa with Mount Sinai. [[Graham Davies]] of [[Cambridge University]] argues that early Jewish pilgrimages identified Jebel Musa as Mount Sinai and this identification was later adopted by the Christian pilgrims.<ref>Davies, Wilderness (1979) pp. 23–24</ref><ref name="ReferenceB">''Mount Sinai'', Joseph J. Hobbs, University of Texas Press, Feb 19, 2014. Social Science</ref> R. K. Harrison states that "Jebel Musa . . . seems to have enjoyed special sanctity long before Christian times, culminating in its identification with Mt. Sinai."<ref name="ReferenceA">Bible Encyclopedia, R. K. Harrison; J. K. Hoffmeier</ref>
Christians settled upon this mountain in the third century AD. [[Georgians]] from the [[Caucasus]] moved to the [[Sinai Peninsula]] in the fifth century, and a Georgian colony was formed there in the ninth century. Georgians erected their own churches in the area of the modern Mount Sinai. The construction of one such church was connected with the name of [[David IV of Georgia|David The Builder]], who contributed to the erection of churches in Georgia and abroad as well. There were political, cultural, and religious motives for locating the church on Mount Sinai. Georgian monks living there were deeply connected with their motherland. The church had its own plots{{Clarify|date=February 2009}} in [[Kartli]]. Some of the Georgian manuscripts of Sinai remain there, but others are kept in [[Tbilisi]], [[St. Petersburg]], [[Prague]], [[New York City]], [[Paris]], or in private collections.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
[[File:دير سانت كاتــرين.jpg|thumb|left|View down to the [[Saint Catherine's Monastery]] from the trail to the summit.]] Some modern biblical scholars{{who|date=November 2018}} now believe that the Israelites would have crossed the Sinai peninsula in a direct route, rather than detouring to the southern tip (assuming that they did not cross the eastern branch of the Red Sea/Reed Sea), and therefore look for the biblical Mount Sinai elsewhere.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}
According to some scholars{{who|date=April 2015}}, the [[Song of Deborah]] suggests that God dwelt at [[Mount Seir]], so many scholars{{who|date=November 2018}} favour a location in [[Nabatea]] (modern Arabia). Alternatively, the biblical descriptions of Sinai can be interpreted as describing a [[volcano]], and so a small number of scholars{{who|date=November 2018}} have considered equating Sinai with locations in northwestern [[Saudi Arabia]], such as [[Jabal al-Lawz]], as there are no volcanoes on the Sinai peninsula.{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}
{{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site | WHS = Saint Catherine Area | Image = Katharinenkloster Sinai BW 2.jpg | Caption = Saint Catherine's Monastery | Criteria = Cultural: i, iii, iv, vi | ID = 954 | Year = 2002 | Area = 60,100 ha }}
==Saint Catherine's Monastery== {{Main|Saint Catherine's Monastery}} Saint Catherine's Monastery ([[Greek language|Greek]]: {{lang|grc|Μονὴ τῆς Ἁγίας Αἰκατερίνης}}) lies on the [[Sinai Peninsula]], at the mouth of an inaccessible gorge at the foot of modern Mount Sinai in Saint Catherine at an elevation of 1550 meters. The monastery is [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] and is a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. According to the UNESCO report (60100 ha / Ref: 954) and website hereunder, this monastery has been called the oldest working Christian monastery in the world&nbsp;– although the [[Monastery of Saint Anthony]], situated across the Red Sea in the desert south of Cairo, also lays claim to that title.
==Ascent== [[File:MtSinaiJune2006.JPG|thumb|left|Sunrise on Mt. Sinai]] There are two principal routes to the summit. The longer and shallower route, ''Siket El Bashait'', takes about 2.5 hours on foot, though [[camel]]s can be used. The steeper, more direct route (''Siket Sayidna Musa'') is up the 3,750 "steps of penitence" in the ravine behind the monastery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allsinai.info/sites/sites/mount%20sinai.htm|publisher=AllSinai.info|title=Mount Sinai}}</ref>
==Summit== [[File:جبل موسى.jpg|thumb|view from the summit of Mount Sinai]] [[File:NearSinaiTop.JPG|thumb|left|The last few meters of the climb up Mount Sinai.]] The summit of the mountain has a [[mosque]] that is still used by Muslims. It also has a [[Greek Orthodox]] chapel, constructed in 1934 on the ruins of a 16th-century church, that is not open to the public. The chapel encloses the rock which is considered to be the source for the biblical [[Tablets of Stone]].<ref name="sacredsites">{{cite web|url=http://www.sacredsites.com/africa/egypt/mount_sinai.html|publisher=Places of Peace and Power|title=Mount Sinai, Egypt}}</ref> At the summit also is "Moses' cave", where Moses was said to have waited to receive the [[Ten Commandments]].
{{Panorama|image=File:MtSinaiPano.jpg|fullwidth=9445|fullheight=1313|caption=View from the summit of Mount Sinai|height=200}}
