In a power system, [[voltage]] at various [[Bus (power engineering)|buses]] tends to increase or decrease during its daily operation. To ensure constant voltage to consumers, various techniques are utilized.

When the voltage is below the required level, reactive power produced by inductance needs to be offset by capacitance.
* [[Synchronous condenser]]s&mdash;can be used to generate reactive power, when they are operated as a motor.
* [[Shunt Capacitance]]&mdash;[[Capacitor]] banks can be connected in [[Series and parallel circuits#Parallel circuits|parallel]] to the transmission lines.
* [[Series Capacitance]]&mdash;Capacitors connected in series, especially for long lines can be used to raise the voltage.
* [[Tap Changing Transformers]]&mdash;Transformer tappings can be automatically changed, to alter the voltage accordingly.

When the voltage is above the required level, reactive power produced by capacitance needs to be offset by inductance.
* [[Shunt Reactors]]&mdash;[[Inductor]] banks can be connected in [[Series and parallel circuits#Parallel circuits|parallel]] to the transmission lines also known as reactors.
* [[Static VAR compensator]]s&mdash;
* [[Tap changer|Tap Changing Transformers]]&mdash;Transformer tappings can be automatically changed, to alter the voltage accordingly.

