{{Energy-stub}}

{{Infobox protected area | name = Yedigöller National Park | alt_name = ''Yedigöller Milli Parkı'' | iucn_category = II | photo = Yedigoller 1163 nevit.jpg | photo_width = 250px | photo_alt = | photo_caption = Yedigöller National Park | map = Turkey| map_alt = | map_caption = | map_width = | relief = yes | location = [[Bolu Province]], [[Turkey]] | nearest_city = [[Istanbul]] | coordinates = {{coords|40.943485|N|31.745502|E|display=inline,title}} | area = {{convert|1623|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}} | established = 1965 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = | label_position = right| label= Yedigöller NP | url = }}
The '''Yedigöller National Park''' ({{lang-tr|Yedigöller}}, "seven lakes") also known as '''Seven Lakes National Park''' is located in the northern part of [[Bolu Province]] in [[Turkey]].<ref name=National>{{Cite web|url=http://nationalparksofturkey.com/yedigoller-seven-lakes-national-park/|title=Yedigoller (Seven Lakes) National Park|accessdate=22 November 2015|publisher=National Parks of Turkey}}</ref><ref name=Panda>{{Cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/how_you_can_help/live_green/travel/on_vacation/eco_tips/turkey/|title=Turkey|work=Green Spots|accessdate=22 November 2015|publisher=WWF Panda Organization}}</ref> The park is categorized under [[IUCN]] II and was established in 1965.{{Sfn|Centre|Areas|1990|p=173}} The park is best known for the seven lakes formed by [[landslide]]s and for its profusion of plant life.<ref name=National/>
==Geography== The park is located at an elevation of {{Convert|900| m}} in [[Mengen, Bolu|Mengen]] district in the north of Bolu Province and to the south of [[Zonguldak]] in the western [[Black Sea]] region. Established in 1965, it encompasses an area of {{Convert|1623|ha}}.<ref name=National/><ref name=News>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/Default.aspx?pageID=447&GalleryID=2659|title=In Photos: Yedigöller National Park lures visitors with colors of autumn|accessdate=22 November 2015|publisher=Hurriyet Daily News}}</ref> There are seven lakes in the park which were formed due to landslides.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kultur.gov.tr/EN,36302/bolu---yedigoller-national-park.html|title=Bolu – Yedigöller National Park|year=2005|accessdate=26 December 2015|publisher=[[Ministry of Culture and Tourism (Turkey)|Republic of Turkey Ministry of Culture and Tourism]]}}</ref> The seven lakes are Büyükgöl, Deringöl, Seringöl, Nazlıgöl, Sazlıgöl, Incegöl and Küçükgöl.<ref name=National/> Several streams flow through the park some of which have handcrafted bridges across them and a small water fall.<ref name=National/><ref name=Parks/>
The park is located between [[Istanbul]] and [[Ankara]]. Access is from the Yenicaga road, {{Convert|152| km}} from the Ankara – Istanbul highway. During the winter the alternate road is only from the Yenicaga – Mengen – Yazicik road.<ref name=Parks>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kultur.gov.tr/EN,36302/bolu---yedigoller-national-park.html|title=National Parks|accessdate=22 November 2015|publisher=Government of Turkey}}</ref> It is {{Convert|42|km}} to the north of Bolu. Kapankaya mountain peak is within the park and provides a vantage location to view the scenic beauty of the park. It is accessible all through the year.<ref name=National/>
The park also has trekking paths and camps to stay,<ref name=News/> in the form of tents, caravans, rest houses and bungalows.<ref name=Parks/> There are also hot springs in the park, and the ski centers here are well known in Turkey.<ref name=National/>
The specific studies related to [[Saprobic]] values of decayed organic matter of the park indicate a range between [[oligosaprobic]] and [[beta-mesosaprobic]] status. The water quality of the streams in the park is classified as Class I and II.<ref name=Gate>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/237615468_Research_on_Ephemeroptera_(Insecta)_Fauna_of_Yedigller_National_Park_(Bolu_Turkey)_water_quality_and_reference_habitat_indicators|title=Research on Ephemeroptera (Insecta) Fauna of Yedigöller National Park (Bolu, Turkey): water quality and reference habitat indicators|accessdate=22 November 2015|publisher =Researchgate Journal}}</ref>
==Flora== [[File:Yedigoller_1891_nevit.jpg|right|thumb|Colourful flora in the park]] The vegetation consists of [[beech tree]]s, [[oak]]s, [[hornbeam]]s, [[fir]]s, elms, hazel nuts, [[spruce]]s, [[alder]]s, lime trees, [[European Black Pine|black pine]]s and Scotch pines.<ref name=National/><ref name=Panda/><ref name=Parks/>
==Fauna== Wildlife within the park includes, but is not limited to, [[red deer]], [[roe deer]], [[wild boar]], [[brown bear]]s, [[Wolf|wolves]], [[red fox]], [[lynx]], [[jungle cat]]s, [[otter]]s and squirrels. As result of better protection conditions in the park the population of animals has increased. The park has an exclusive protected area for deer. A [[trout]] farm has also been established in the park.<ref name=National/><ref name=Parks/> New insect species ''[[Ephemeroptera]]'' identified in the park are ''Ecdyonurus starmachi,'' ''Paraleptophlebia cincta,'' ''Caenis martae,'' and ''Baetis lapponicus.''<ref name=Gate/>
